Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

I want to study social work. I will work with children who have been abused or neglected. I will help troubled families. My values for social work are service, respect, and ethical nature. I want to help improve relationships. I also want to improve myself.

I always wanted to help others. I was unsure of my career path. During high school and college, I saw many people avoid problems. Some used bad ways to cope. Because of this, I studied Psychology. After college, I did not know what to do. Then, one summer, I visited a friend. She showed me a boy who needed help. He was 16 and he wanted to escape his abusive parents. I went to his house and talked to the police. They asked me to talk to his parents. The parents were nervous. They blamed their son. This made me think about social work.

Social justice is important. We say the individual is important, but we are not unique. We strive to be like everyone else. I am an individual. I do not like limits. In high school and college, I protested social injustice. I colored my hair differently, wore special clothes, pierced my ears, and joined GSBA. I fought against racism and discrimination. I believe in social justice.

The paper talks about Biological and Sociocultural models of insomnia. The Biological model looks at genes and health. The Sociocultural model looks at the environment and people's groups. The review explains sleep problems and how these models help understand them.

A sleep problem can be a main sleep problem, a sleep problem with another mental problem, or a sleep problem with other things. Main sleep problems are Dyssomnias or Parasomnias. Other sleep problems come from medical issues or medicines. Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia is a problem with getting or staying asleep. Primary Hypersomnia is a problem with staying awake. Narcolepsy is a problem with sudden sleep and dreams. Parasomnias are sleep problems with bad behaviors or body things. Parasomnias are: Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The review focuses on insomnia and some main sleep problems.

The Biological model of sleep problems looks at genes, heritable things, and sleep problems with the body. Neurons in the brain have something called orexin that controls sleep and being awake. A study with mice found that a certain type of special receptor on these neurons controls sleep. If this receptor doesn't work, people might have sleep problems. The study shows that mice and humans are similar in this way. If this receptor is not normal, people might need medicine to sleep well. This can affect school, work, and daily life.

This paper talks about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it gives a simple definition. Then, it explains how to diagnose CAPD. Finally, it talks about how a teacher can help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

CAPD means the brain has trouble processing sounds. People with CAPD can hear normally but have problems understanding or using sound information. CAPD was first talked about in the 1950s. In 1954, Italian researchers started testing children with communication problems. In 1961, Kimura made a test for the brain's sound processing. A big meeting in 1977 helped more research on CAPD.

CAPD makes it hard to do many things with sound. A person might have problems with:
- hearing sound in space
- telling one sound from another
- understanding sound patterns
- picking up changes in speech
- hearing sounds in order

To diagnose CAPD, doctors test how a person hears and answers questions. There is no one test that works well, and the cause is not known. Some tests ask people to pick out sounds or words among many. Other tests record sounds in the ear and check the brain's response.

Twelfth Night says that disguise can be useful for a long time, but in the end, one must stop being someone else to not lose themselves forever. Ending deception can also cause alienation. One must choose between saving themselves and keeping relationships. Some people will be upset if they find out they were tricked. The topic of gender role reversal in deception is difficult because it raises questions. Why does the person need to pretend to be the other gender? In Viola’s case, she becomes a man to protect herself. She feels safe in a new country by pretending to be a boy. She is so convincing that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian and falls in love with her. Viola also has to manage romantic feelings for someone else, like Orsino. Twelfth Night shows that deception can help people talk about hidden feelings. Olivia and Orsino might have unexpressed desires. Olivia’s feelings for Cesario might not be about liking men, but about how they look. Olivia easily switches her love from Cesario to Sebastian and sees Viola as family.

German colonial rule was known for being very bad. It was very bad, especially in South West Africa. Many people were hurt, like the Ovaherero and Nama. But the German empire had many different rules and ways to run things. Education was different in each place. In some colonies, like East Africa, the government helped teach people. In South West Africa, it was mostly the missionaries. The government helped Europeans, but not Africans much. This made South West Africa different. The paper wants to talk about why this happened. There are many books about German colonial education. Most are in German and old. The paper wants to look at new research about what settlers and colonial leaders thought about Africans. South West Africa had a comfortable climate, but not much water. Few people lived there. The whole area was not good for farming.

The music called "Heavy Metal" is very old. It has many kinds. It started 40 years ago. There are many sub-kinds and smaller kinds. Each kind has its own sound. Heavy Metal is known for being loud and strong. It has heavy sounds. It can make people feel many things, like anger or sadness. It is also known for having many people playing together. In the past, many Heavy Metal bands used drugs to make their music. They wanted to make music that felt strange and new. Heavy Metal music is also influenced by other music from long ago, like the Romantic Era. Lyrics tell stories about darkness and feeling bad. An example is the song "Helter Skelter" by the Beatles. This song helped start Heavy Metal.

Before Surrealists made dreamlike paintings, artist Henri Rousseau painted his dreams. In 1910, he made "The Dream." This painting shows a woman in awe of a beautiful land. It also shows Rousseau’s own dreams. He wanted to be praised by other artists and art lovers. But he faced a hard choice. He could either copy other styles of painting or be unique with his own style.

Before we talk about "The Dream," we need to know about Rousseau's life. He was born in Laval, France, in 1844. His father was a tinsmith. Rousseau had no art training. He worked for France as a toll service employee until he was forty. He lost his first wife and eight infant children. After that, he painted to feel better. Unlike other artists, he painted like a folk artist.

Rousseau wanted art world acceptance. He was not well-educated in painting. He began his career late. Many other artists were doing well. He started getting good reviews at the same time as Matisse.

Many smart people think ethics and beauty are connected. I agree. John Keats says, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty — That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Most people learn about ethics and beauty from school or life. But people often like them without learning them. Ethics and beauty try to explain, not make rules. We talk about good art or morals, but words cannot fully explain why they are good. People say, "There's just something about it" about their favorite art or books. Art and morals have a special, hard-to-explain part. This makes them similar. Kant says ethics cannot be fully explained. I think this special part is what makes art and morality powerful. It connects them.

Art and morality affect us deeply. They change us. Kant says literature is important because it has moral values. We need values in life. Literature is special because it teaches us these values.

Today, Germany is strong and united. The country has a unique culture. It comes from many different sources and tribes. The country has a long history. The ancient Romans called this land Germania. The name comes from different sources. Some say it is from the Germans' spear, or their loud voices. Others say it is from the Romans' word for their neighbors. The Romans often fought with the Germanic tribes. They called them Germans. The early Romans wrote about the Germans. They said the Germans were strong and did not mix with other races. The Romans traded with the Germans. They also used the Germans in their army. The Germans lived near the Romans. They traded their goods and skills.

I looked down, my mind empty. I saw a picture. I felt nothing. My mind was busy, but not thinking real thoughts. I was just seeing and feeling. I had a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." It teaches how to draw. One trick is to put a frame around the picture. This makes the picture easy to see. I tried it with a bowl of fruit. I couldn't do it. I was too amazed. I wanted to draw since I was six. I tried to draw. My hand moved. Water moved. The brown thing in the toilet would not flush. I used the mop. My hand felt like it was in an oven. I finished the job. I felt proud.

Teenagers are dying in cars. This happens because the teen brain is not ready for driving. Teenagers don't have enough experience. This causes more accidents and other problems. Many teens drive with friends, which is dangerous. A study shows this. California and other states try to make teen driving safer with special licenses. But these licenses are only temporary. The real problem is that teens are not ready for driving. Marvin Zuckerman says 18 is too young for a regular license. He says teens want to take risks. We should delay driving until teens are older. If we don't, more teens will die. Many baby boomers' children will drive soon. We need a law to help this. Schools could teach driving. No one under 18 could drive. A permit could be given, but only after learning and practice. This law would help all teens in America. It's not a new idea.

I looked at old Edison films in Library of Congress. There were 15 trick films from 1895 to 1901. I saw these films use creative editing to make illusions. My study focused on describing tricks in most films and looking at some later films that were different.

Most trick films in the early 1900s were set-bound. They did not move the camera. They used long and medium shots. They followed the rule one shot = one film. These films were like stage shows. They showed whole performances. Actors did not move towards or away from the camera. They moved side to side. Even when they left the frame, the camera did not follow.

The films were often long shots. Close-up shots were not used. This was like in theatre and vaudeville, where people see the whole show. The length of the films was short, often a minute or less. The films showed tricks, like magic or disappearing acts. Sometimes, one "shot" was many shots joined together to make illusions.

John Taylor, from Caroline, was a early and strong supporter of Republicanism. He loved farming, but also had a short time in politics. This made him known for his strong views on freedom and government.

Taylor believed the United States could create an ideal government because there was no old tradition to stop them. He believed in natural rights, which are all connected. If one is denied, all fail. These rights should be beyond government control.

Taylor wanted a government that understands good and evil in people. He thought that government should protect private property, improve farming, and stop capitalism. A good government would work even if led by people with bad intentions. Taylor believed people are naturally bad, but a good government can control this.

Taylor wanted a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He wanted a small government with only the powers in the Constitution. He knew an extensive government could be bad. But he also thought a simple interpretation could be dangerous and corrupt. He thought the Declaration of Independence was the true law of the United States.

In December, fewer people submit commuter logs. This could be because of winter and busy schoolwork. December is also a busy holiday season with a long campus break. This may explain why February has low log submissions. People may get less excited about the project over time. We try to fix this with a March campaign called the Carpool Challenge. Another problem is that people like driving cars. We give out gift cards to encourage alternative commuting. But to make the project better, we could also give away cars like bicycles, hybrids, or electrics. This could help more people join.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a type of security. It tries to match an index, a commodity, or a group of assets. ETFs trade like stocks on an exchange. They offer many benefits. For example, they can be sold short, bought on margin, and purchased with one share. They also have lower expense ratios than mutual funds. However, trades with ETFs cost a commission, like buying a stock.

ETFs have many types of funds. It is good for investors to check if stated benefits like diversification are true. We will look at the ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings. We will see if owning one ETF is better than owning many stocks.

We will only use the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF. Here are the top 10 holdings and their percentages:

To see how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF, we will use the current asset percentages. We will calculate the Beta and Return if the portfolio had these 10 stocks in the same proportions as the ETF.

The chart shows that the top 10 holdings have a higher return and a lower Beta than the ETF. The return is 6.11% higher, which is a 16% increase. The Beta is 0.12 lower. It seems that owning just the top 10 holdings could give a better return with less risk. However, the portfolios might not be different in a statistical way.

To check if the portfolios are different, we will find the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks. We will compare this to the standard deviation of the ETF IHF.

Edgar Allan Poe's poem “Dream-Land” is one of his best. In this poem, he uses the word “Thule” from an old Greek story. Virgil wrote about this place, which was far away north of Britain. Some people think Poe got this idea from a German writer named Goethe. Karl Arndt says Poe copied some parts from Goethe's poem “The King of Thule.” In this poem, a king loses his wife and becomes very sad. He drinks too much and dies. Poe's “Dream-Land” is like reading a continuation of this story. The speaker in “Dream-Land” feels lonely and sees a dark, colorless place. Poe uses Thule twice in his writings. He also wrote about “ultma Thule” in another poem. These two poems can be read together. Poe liked Goethe's work because Tennyson admired him. Poe knew about Goethe through Tennyson and many others who talked about his writings.

In California, a customer could get extra money if they show store manager did not clean spill and cared about eating dinner. Judge is not likely to dismiss claim. To win, customer must show manager did wrong on purpose. If many people fell before, and manager still did not clean, customer can say manager acted poorly. Manager told employees to not clean spill and was on dinner break. Store had many falls. Customer slipped and got hurt. Now, customer is suing for more money. California law allows extra money if store manager did something bad on purpose. Manager could have cleaned spill but did not. He did not care about customer safety.

Four years ago, I took a class about Islam at CBC. Many class discussions were about whether Islam is a hostile religion. This topic is even more important now. After 9/11, I saw media change from being against Islam to being very accepting of it. In 2001, a Muslim president candidate was impossible. The Prophet Muhammad's biography intrigued me. It said he was a peaceful person, not a conqueror. But history says he forced people to become Muslim. This story makes Muhammad look like a kind and gentle prophet. But I think this is not true. The biography has many stories with third-hand sources. These stories make Muhammad look good. But history shows he was not a kind person. I think Muslims know this about Muhammad.

Jesus' teachings and beliefs were forgotten as Christianity grew. Today, many people want to return to what Jesus said. This will happen in the future. People will remove what was added to Christianity later. They will go back to Jesus' original ideas. This will make Christianity more the same, not different. This has happened before. For example, the Romans, who killed Christians, became Christian later. The United States went from slavery to African-American leadership. This will happen in Christianity too. People will read Jesus' words as stories, not as rules. What happened to make Christianity change? Long ago, there was only Judaism. This became the start of Christianity. The Romans took control of Jerusalem. At that time, Jews did not agree. They divided into groups with different beliefs.

I think The Jungle shows how people are naturally greedy and selfish. They only want good things for themselves and not for others. This book shows this in many ways. One big example is the factory owners and managers. They just want their companies and factories to be big. They do not care about anyone or anything that gets hurt by their factories. Sinclair writes, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." He wants to show the damage this pollution is doing. They do not care about the smoke from the factories or the waste from the animal pens.

The owners and managers also do not care about their workers. They only want to make more money. They make workers work long hours and can lay off many people at once without any help. During the time The Jungle is set, there were no laws to protect workers. This let managers and owners do what they wanted. Workers had no way to escape this bad system. They were forced to work in bad conditions and had no help. The book does not say this directly, but workers were like slaves. There were unions, but they did not help much. They made money from the poor workers. The workers were so badly treated that they could not get out of the system.

Many writers use different ways to make readers feel or think certain things about important topics. One way is using words like adjectives and nouns that do not usually go together. Another way is giving special meaning to symbols and then using those symbols to make readers feel something about an important subject.

F. Scott Fitzgerald does this in his book The Great Gatsby. He uses colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink to make readers feel something. He gives special meaning to white/gray, with white being more high-class and gray being older and faded. In the book, people like Daisy and Jordan always wear white, and the party halls are colorful. Later, Fitzgerald uses white/gray to show that people or things are unimportant. For example, Daisy is often in white, which makes her seem like just something Gatsby wants.

Fitzgerald does this with many other colors too. He gives special meaning to these colors and then uses them to show readers something about important subjects.

San Diego County is a good place for growing many plants. The weather is usually mild and sunny. Common crops are tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. People in the area like organic food. Many farms offer tours and let people hike or watch birds. The landowner can use government programs to help with costs and improve the land for wildlife. This can also make more money and teach people. Organic farming often has more biodiversity but costs more. It needs more work to grow plants without chemicals. Small farms may not be as efficient as large farms.

The land chosen for this example is 160 acres near the town of Potrero. It is next to the Cleveland National Forest. It has chaparral, nonnative grassland, and oak woodland. Many plants and animals live here, some are rare or may disappear soon. Native Americans lived here for a long time, then cattle ranchers and wood sellers came.

The landowner researched government programs to help with farming costs and protect wildlife. They also found a successful organic farm nearby for a model.

Culture is very important in negotiations. Culture is not the same everywhere. It is not just one thing. It is not always the same. People should not say "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are nice." These are too simple and not correct.

To understand a foreign culture, study its history and learn about its beliefs. Do not judge or try to change it. Accept it as it is. This is especially true when negotiating with a culture that is different from yours. If you are in a foreign country, respect their traditions and beliefs. This will help you talk with people who are different from you.

Culture is not just about countries. Companies also have their own culture. Some companies work long hours, others work less. You can see a company's culture in how employees dress, how they talk, and how they hire people. Some companies let employees help with charities. Some do not. Even in one country, you can find many different company cultures.

Values are also important. They tell us why a culture is the way it is. If a culture values saving face, a negotiator will not make others look bad. If a culture values hard work, a negotiator will not give up easily. Before a negotiation, it is good to know about these things.

But it is also good to learn about the other person. This can make the negotiation better.

St. Anselm believed God exists because it is in our minds. He said, “God is that than which nothing greater can be thought.” So, if we can think of God, he must exist. He did not need proof from outside our minds. This is called faith.

Thomas Aquinas thought God could be proven by reason and evidence. He made five arguments. For example, he said everything changes, so there must be a creator. He did not need faith. This is called logic.

Both had good points but neither proved God fully.

Buddha was a prince who lived long ago. He became a wise teacher and created Buddhism. This religion is now 2500 years old. It is different today than when Buddha was alive. For example, in Sri Lanka, a country where Theravada Buddhism is popular, there is a special ceremony called the water-cutting ceremony. Both monks and people who are not monks take part in this. It is a religious event, but Buddha never told people to do it. This shows that the religion has changed over time, both in its traditions and its most important beliefs.

There are special words that we will use in this talk. "Internal" means something that happens within the Buddhist community, no matter if the person is a monk or not. "External" means something that happens outside the Buddhist community. A "hostile" force is one that hurts or wants to hurt the Buddhist community. A "benign" force is one that does not want to hurt or help the Buddhist community but might do so by accident.

First, we need to look at the basic beliefs of Buddhism. Buddhists seek help from the "three jewels": Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha. Dhamma is the Buddhist teachings found in the Tripitaka, which has three parts: Sutta Pitaka (teachings), Vinaya Pitaka (rules), and Abhidhamma Pitaka (metaphysical ideas). Important ideas in Buddhism include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (life is suffering), and Anicca (everything is changing). To stop the cycle of death and rebirth (Sansara), one must recognize these ideas and stop having desire (lobha), hatred (dosa), and delusion (moha). The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for life. Laypeople have five rules: no killing, no lying, no stealing, no sexual misconduct, and no intoxicating substances. Monks have many more rules. The most important belief in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: life is suffering, attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico had a long history of rivalry from 1836 to 1893. The worst part was the Mexican-American War in 1846-1848. The United States won and got Texas and the American Southwest. Many other fights also happened, but they stopped before World War I. The rivalry started because of religion, culture, and money. People from the United States and Mexico had different beliefs and wanted more land. This is similar to other countries that live next to each other and have rivalries. David M. Pletcher said that Mexico and Cuba had long rivalries with the United States. They were close neighbors and had different beliefs. Other Latin American countries had good relations with the United States. Sally Frahm said that Americans in the 1800s were against Catholicism and monarchy. The rivalry between the United States and Mexico was partly about beliefs. Diehl and Goerts list 17 disputes between the two countries. Most were about borders and fights between bandits. The rivalry stopped when Mexico became more dependent on the United States and American goals changed from taking land to helping Mexico with money.

Five years ago, I got very sick. I was a nurse. I chose this job because I needed to feel safe. I thought, "People always need nurses." So, I did not become a scientist or journalist like I wanted. But now, I am 46, single, and cannot work. I have no money. I get help from my family and friends. These people make my life better. Without them, I would feel very weak. I think we need to trust each other more in America. We should help each other, not just rely on big government. Our founders crossed the Rockies with wagon trains, not alone. They worked together. So, be ready. I have a disaster kit. I know how to prepare. But also, know your neighbors. They can help too.

Why do organisms change? Are there rules that guide this change? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson said that even today, scientists cannot explain simple organic shapes with math. Now, math is used to study mollusk skeletons and their growth. Our study uses math and tests to find how mollusks change. We used X-ray pictures to find how many curves and sizes are in their shells. We put these numbers into a computer program to see different shell shapes. This helps understand big changes in mollusk evolution. Shells are like tubes that change over time. The shell’s shape and size changes as the animal grows. Viewing a shell from different sides helps see its shape and size. To count whorls, start at the shell’s beginning and draw a line. Count whorls from this line. The shell’s path can be drawn and changed to see how it grows.

For the last ten years, in Indonesia, baby and newborn death rates stayed the same. They didn't improve much. The country is close to meeting many goals like clean water and sanitation. But child and mother health got worse. There are many reasons for this. It's time to fix the health system, not just focus on small programs.

Indonesia did well with skilled workers at births. Now, 72% of births have a skilled worker. But some workers can't help if the birth is hard. This is why many mothers die from bleeding. Also, fewer children under five get help for diarrhea. Post-birth care data is not good. It's low everywhere.

Cesarean rates are too low, only 4%. They are low everywhere, but lowest in the country. This is unfair. People in cities get more help. The poor can't get help because it's too expensive.

To fix this, should Indonesia focus on making the health system better or fix specific programs? Both ways have pros and cons. Vertical programs can fix problems faster. But they can also hurt other areas and cause duplication. This can waste money and time.

Victorian novels focus on detail and the aristocracy. Two Victorian novels, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They use mystery and strange happenings to make characters more interesting. These novels use dreams or dreamlike states to show characters' thoughts and feelings.

In Oliver Twist, these dreams help us understand Oliver's pain and confusion. When he is shot, he relives the event in a dream. He can't control what happens. This shows that Oliver doesn't have control over his life. He is overwhelmed and feels defeated. Someone else is probably causing his misfortune.

The same day keeps coming and going. It's always black and quiet. It's never really day or night. This shows the constant pain and fear that Oliver feels.

Two years ago, I worked after school, teaching young students. I helped them with subjects they struggled with. I was good at teaching English and reading. One of my jobs was to help a boy named Adrian. He had problems reading. I noticed he understood some letters but not others. He spoke English well, but he didn't know the alphabet. His mother spoke Spanish. She couldn't speak any English. I only knew a little Spanish. But we talked and I realized Adrian could read but didn't know the alphabet. I hope he's better now.

I tell this story to talk about language problems in schools. It's not always simple. Even kids who speak English can have problems. I think everyone knows this. So, what do we do? For kids like Adrian, the solution is simple: teach reading and the alphabet. But for kids who don't speak English, it's harder. There's no one solution. We need to combine all methods: dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes.

First, the dual language system is good. It helps all kids, not just Spanish speakers. "Children in these programs do better academically." Some people say it's a waste of resources. But that's not true. If we have these programs in all schools, all kids will benefit. But we can't make all teachers bilingual. That's not realistic. However, we can have bilingual helpers to support teachers.

Many people learn about something bigger than themselves when they are young. Some go to church or temple. Some search inside themselves. Others accept their parents' beliefs. Some people do not believe in anything bigger. They think only about themselves. Some change their beliefs many times. Everyone has their own unique way to think about spirituality. We look for light to guide us out of darkness.

My father liked cardinals, red birds. He told me this one day. We sat on our porch, listening to the rain. He looked out, thinking about the past. He was sick and weak. I was scared and did not want to talk about his death. I hugged him. We sat together and watched the rain.

My father died in December, five months after I turned 22. The medicine did not make him feel better. It only made him live longer. I did not want to watch him die. I did not want to remember him by how he died. I stayed in bed for three days. No one called me.

The Gothic novel is a mix of old and new. It is called a "Gothic Novel" but uses both old and new ideas. Ian Watt says this in "The Rise of the Gothic Novel". The Gothic mode has both good and bad words. Some people say it has no real depth, but others like the "terrible sublime" it shows. The first Gothic novel was "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole. He used old ideas from ancient and modern romances. He also used new ways to tell stories. The word "gothic" was used for many things, but it meant old or simple. Walpole used this to create a new kind of story. The Gothic genre has many old ideas from medieval times. Even then, "gothic" meant old. The mix of old and new makes Gothic stories last for a long time. It is old and new to readers today. The most important Gothic idea is chivalry. It is the idea of a proper knight. Chivalry is important because it shows how knights were supposed to be good, brave, and competent. Walpole wrote "The Castle of Otranto" in a time with much politics and trouble. He was worried about the future. He may have thought society had lost the good values of the Gothic era. He shows this in the character Frederic. He is a prince and has suffered much. Frederic has many chivalric traits. He is brave and courteous, like a knight. Walpole starts this story with old ideas and uses them in a new way.

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from customers' orders to the customer. It was invented in 1982 by Keith Oliver. He explained how to plan, do, and control the supply chain to meet customers' needs quickly and well. There are six important parts of a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these parts to give the best service to customers.

Production is the first step in the supply chain. It is important because it shows when, why, where, and how to make things. To know what customers want, managers look at the market. The market shows what customers need. Once managers understand this, they decide what to make and how much. Then, they decide where to make it. They choose the best place for volume and quality, considering customer demand.

After choosing the place, managers plan the work and maintain equipment. This is very important. Every detail needs to be planned well. If not, it can cost the company much time and money. For example, I worked at Wal-Mart and Target. Both companies have rules and plans for everything, like employee uniforms and receiving shipments.

The second important part is supply. This means making decisions about facilities and working with other companies. A company may have many parts to make one product. Each part has different tools, workers, and skills. The manager must choose the best part for each job. Some jobs may be done by other companies to speed up the process and reduce costs.

Hitler is not alive in Burma. Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street. She holds a piece of cardboard. The message says, "Hitler is alive in Burma."

Burma is a country in Southeast Asia. A bad group, the military junta, rules it. They came to power in 1962. In 2007, monks led protests. The government allowed peaceful protests at first. But then violence happened. The military attacked monasteries. Journalists were imprisoned. Kenji Nagai, a Japanese journalist, was killed.

There are many examples of bad governments. Early Roman emperors said they ruled as gods. In Japan, emperors are believed to be gods. Our president, George W. Bush, talks to Ted Haggard.

In 1989, people protested in Tiananmen Square. They wanted to stop the bad government. The death count is not clear. Another example is the Rwandan genocide. Hutu militia groups killed Tutsis and political moderates. Another example is Hitler's Third Reich. Many Jews were killed.

Duke Ellington's jazz music lasts long because of his good skills. He wrote many songs for his band. Ellington played piano in some songs, but his writing is the main part of his music. He made sure each band member could play well. He also wrote songs with solo spots for the band members to play their best. Ellington wrote pieces that sound good together. He knew how to make each player's sound fit with the rest of the band. This made him write some of the best jazz songs. The Grove Music dictionary says Ellington used voice as a musical instrument. Creole Love Call is a song where he does this. It has six parts, each with a different sound. Ellington used voice to make a song's sound richer. In Hot and Bothered, Ellington used a muted trumpet and scat singing to make a good sound. It Don't Mean a Thing is another song where he used a main band member to make the melody.

She always felt something was missing. This feeling started when she was 14. It stayed with her for 3 years, until she was 17. She wanted a person, not a thing. But she didn't like any boys. Some tried to be friends, but she wasn't interested. She wondered what was wrong. She didn't know what caused this.

A normal day at home was peaceful. Her parents were calm and never argued. They only argued about her being independent. She was the opposite of her parents. They were calm, she was fun and nice.

Today was not like other days. She heard a scream from the kitchen. Her mother was hurt. She ran to help. Her mother said, "Take me to the hospital." She carried her mother to the car and drove to the hospital.

At the hospital, there was a smell of sickness. But she was only thinking about helping her mother. She called for doctors. They took her mother away. She was left to wait.

Her mother fell from a stool while trying to get a vase from a high cabinet.

This study showed that following the Mediterranean Diet, as shown by a high "alternate Mediterranean" diet score, can reduce the risk of heart disease and stroke. The "alternate Mediterranean" diet includes more plant foods, monounsaturated fats, and fish, and less animal products and saturated fats. It also allows moderate alcohol intake.

Previous studies found that this diet also helps reduce heart disease and stroke risk. This study examined 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, without heart disease or diabetes, from the Nurses' Health Study.

The study lasted 20 years, collecting data six times using food frequency questionnaires. More than 95% of the women stayed in the study. The questionnaires measured their diet for the past year. The results were confirmed by medical records. The study adjusted for factors like age, smoking, body mass index, and physical activity.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean Diet, as shown by a higher diet score, reduced the risk of heart disease and stroke in women. Out of 20 years of follow-up, there were 2391 cases of heart disease, 1763 cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular deaths. Women with the highest diet score had a 30% lower risk compared to those with the lowest score.

In 2007, America's money problem was very bad. Many people were out of work, the house prices fell, and big companies were in trouble. This problem still happens today, so we need to find out how it started and stop it. The money problem came from people in charge making bad choices. They made banks give loans to people who could not pay back. They also packaged these loans into things called CDOs and CDS. When people could not pay back, the banks had no money. This made the problem worse. The problem started in the late 1990s when President Clinton was trying to keep his job. He changed rules to make it easier to give loans. This led to the big problem in 2007. Many things made the problem worse. People used new kinds of loans in the housing market. This made the housing market very important to the economy. The housing market started to fall, and the banks that bought the loan packages had big debts. Some big banks had to sell, and Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were taken over by the government.

Exposition is not good. It tells too much, too fast. It makes people sleepy or press "Back." Dr. Merlin hates Too Much Information.

"Show, don't tell" is a good rule. But many writers use exposition. It's like saying, "The heroine met her husband here. They married here. He died here." Readers don't like this. They want to feel the story.

Instead, describe the husband's speech and actions. Show how he loves his wife. Show how she feels about him. This makes readers care about him and her. When he dies, they feel sad for her.

You must give readers meat. Don't skip details. Even small details help. For example, the husband's Air Force past, his job, his dreams. These help readers understand him.

Sometimes it's hard to add details. But not adding them makes the story weak. Readers need to feel the story. So, add the details. Make your story interesting.

I watched two news reports from Columbus, Ohio. One was live on NBC 4. It was about a man named Shad Hostettler who stabbed his wife. They showed his picture. He looked very bad. They spoke about it for two minutes. I thought that was enough.

The second story was about a young man named Travis Buyers. He was shot in Sharon Woods. He was very hurt. They did not say who did it. The police were looking for the person.

The third story was about a hole in a helicopter. They thought it was made by a small gun. They were looking for the person who did it.

The fourth story was about a storm. They said it would rain and be hot later.

The fifth story was about a store robbery. A dark man robbed it. They said he wore a hoodie. They spoke much about how dark he was.

The last story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug kingpin. They said he went to prison for 300 months.

Brothers have strong bond. This bond has many emotions: love, pride, anger, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other. When brother see other, they see themselves. This bond shows in good or bad times. Emotions cause problems. Part of bond is dealing with consequences. When brother look at other, they see true self. Actions show true character. In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this bond and feelings. They go on journey. They have many emotions. One brother dies. Theme shows through characters and narrator.

Protagonist feels pride. He wants brother to do things he likes. Brother cannot do these things. Brother has weak heart. Protagonist has dreams. Brother dies. Protagonist feels angry. Then, he loves brother. He wants to keep brother alive. He feels hope when brother smiles. He wants to stay with brother.

The brain is complex. It is a system that uses information. As technology changed, so did the ways people talk about the brain. At first, it was like a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and now like a computer. Remember, these ways to talk about the brain are not always right.

Information starts with senses. These change physical things into signals. The brain changes these signals. It does this in two ways: bottom-up and top-down. Bottom-up means putting small pieces together to make something bigger. Top-down means using what you already know to help. For example, when you look at a black box, bottom-up helps you see it. Top-down helps you decide it is a black box, not a hole.

After this, the brain decides what is important. This is called attention. It helps you notice your name in a noisy room, but not blades of grass.

The brain also needs to store information. There are many types of memory. Sensory memory is for what you see, hear, etc. Working memory is for what you use right now. Long-term memory is for what you remember for a long time. Information is stored in different ways: structurally, phonemically, or semantically.

There are many ways to understand how the brain stores knowledge. One way is the semantic network model. It says there are nodes for concepts. These nodes are linked based on how related they are. For example, “chair” is linked to “table” and “wooden.”

Aldous Huxley worries about future problems with technology and capitalism. In Brave New World, people value society over individuals. They want happiness, but do not think for themselves. The World Controller controls them. Marxist ideas help explain this. Huxley uses Marxist words like "homogeny" and "reification" to show problems with the economy.

Capitalism is shown as "false consciousness." People do not understand their place in the economy. The World Controller makes them want to buy and spend. This is like "hegemony," where a group controls others. Lower classes do not know they are being controlled. Most Alphas and Betas in the story accept their place. This shows how people in Brave New World are obedient to the system.

Relationships are simple. People do not have deep feelings. They talk about women's looks. Men and women do not love each other. They only want to be together because of their place in society. This shows how capitalism affects people's lives. They follow rules and do not question their status. This is like the Marxist idea of the proletariat.

I have been a student at University Park for 2.5 years, or 4.5 semesters. Many students, including me, find it hard to get around campus. My first year, I lived in East Halls, far from the center of campus. Walking to classes like those in Willard building could take 25 minutes. An old student told me that East Halls was once far from other buildings. Now, there are sports fields and new buildings. As the campus grows, it is harder to move around. What is the best solution? Bicycles are good for students, but we need better bike paths.

I talked to a friend who started biking again. He said, "Bikes are best for getting around." They are good for health and travel. I live off campus now, as far from the center as some dorms. I bought a bike this year. It takes 5 minutes to ride from my home to Thomas building, saving 30-40 minutes. The Pollock Road to Thomas is not always easy. If I didn’t have my bike, I would have to walk, taking 2.5 hours a week. That’s too much time. Without a bike, I would spend more time walking to classes, appointments, etc. That’s why I need my bike.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa.
